int-org-section.p:
In December 2006 the Council adopted a decision establishing the Seventh Framework Programme for research and technological development (FP7, which was implemented during 2007–13), and also established the Seventh Framework Programme of Euratom, for nuclear research and training activities in 2007–11. In October 2010 the Commission adopted a communication on the Innovation Union, designed to help the EU economy to recover from economic crisis, by encouraging global competitiveness and innovation. FP7 was superseded by the EU Framework Programme for Research and Innovation, `Horizon 2020’, covering 2014–20, with a budget of some €80,000m. In 2015, under Horizon 2020, the three policy objectives of open innovation, open science, and open to the world were established. Horizon 2020 was superseded by Horizon Europe for 2021–27, with a budget of €76,400m. (in 2018 prices), plus additional funding of some €8,000m. Horizon Europe introduced a new European Innovation Council (EIC), intended to complement the work of the EIT. The EIC, which became operational in 2018–20 during a pilot phase, supports innovation by means of two funding instruments: the EIC Pathfinder supports researchers investigating `high risk, high gain’ new technologies, while the EIC Accelerator supports innovative projects being developed by small and medium-sized Enterprises (SMEs). The EIC became fully operational in March 2021, and a new European Innovation Council and SMEs Executive Agency was established in Brussels. The EU’s research and innovation budget for 2021–27 (in 2018 prices) also allocated €1,757m. to the Euratom Research and Training Programme and €5,000m. to the International Thermonuclear Experimental Reactor (ITER—see 
Energy, Environment and Climate
).
